{"parse":{"title":"Nilavilakku","pageid":8437798,"revid":835963557,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Nilavilakku</b> is a traditional <a href=\"/wiki/Oil_lamp\" title=\"Oil lamp\">lamp</a> used commonly in <a href=\"/wiki/Kerala\" title=\"Kerala\">Kerala</a> as well as in <a href=\"/wiki/Tamil_nadu\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Tamil nadu\">Tamil nadu</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Dance_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Dance-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The traditional lamps which is lit during every auspicious occasions; in temples before the worship starts; at the official and unofficial functions.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Etymology\">Etymology</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nilavilakku&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Etymology\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Nilavilakku_Different_sizes.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/94/Nilavilakku_Different_sizes.jpg/220px-Nilavilakku_Different_sizes.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"293\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/94/Nilavilakku_Different_sizes.jpg/330px-Nilavilakku_Different_sizes.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/94/Nilavilakku_Different_sizes.jpg/440px-Nilavilakku_Different_sizes.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1200\" data-file-height=\"1600\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Nilavilakku_Different_sizes.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Nilavilakku</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Nilavilak,_%E0%B4%A8%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B2%E0%B4%B5%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B3%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Nilavilak%2C_%E0%B4%A8%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B2%E0%B4%B5%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B3%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D.JPG/220px-Nilavilak%2C_%E0%B4%A8%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B2%E0%B4%B5%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B3%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Nilavilak%2C_%E0%B4%A8%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B2%E0%B4%B5%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B3%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D.JPG/330px-Nilavilak%2C_%E0%B4%A8%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B2%E0%B4%B5%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B3%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Nilavilak%2C_%E0%B4%A8%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B2%E0%B4%B5%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B3%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D.JPG/440px-Nilavilak%2C_%E0%B4%A8%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B2%E0%B4%B5%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B3%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"3072\" data-file-height=\"2304\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Nilavilak,_%E0%B4%A8%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B2%E0%B4%B5%E0%B4%BF%E0%B4%B3%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D%E0%B4%95%E0%B5%8D.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Syrian Christian Nilavilakku</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Nilavilak,a_tradition_lamp.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Nilavilak%2Ca_tradition_lamp.jpg/220px-Nilavilak%2Ca_tradition_lamp.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"165\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Nilavilak%2Ca_tradition_lamp.jpg/330px-Nilavilak%2Ca_tradition_lamp.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5c/Nilavilak%2Ca_tradition_lamp.jpg/440px-Nilavilak%2Ca_tradition_lamp.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"4000\" data-file-height=\"3000\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Nilavilak,a_tradition_lamp.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>a lighted up nilavilakku</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Aal_vilakku.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Aal_vilakku.jpg/220px-Aal_vilakku.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"391\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Aal_vilakku.jpg/330px-Aal_vilakku.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/23/Aal_vilakku.jpg/440px-Aal_vilakku.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2304\" data-file-height=\"4096\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Aal_vilakku.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Bronze lamp used in Temples.</div></div></div>\n<p><i>Nilam</i> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Malayalam\" title=\"Malayalam\">Malayalam</a>/<a href=\"/wiki/Tamil_language\" title=\"Tamil language\">Tamil</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-Dance_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Dance-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> language means <i>floor or the ground</i> and <i>vilakku</i> means lamp.\nThe Nilavilakku is integral to several rituals and ceremonies in Hindu families in Kerala. As the sun sets, young girls of the family bring the lighted lamps to the verandah of the house, continued with evening prayers. In the evening the ritual is repeated alongside evening prayers. In Hindu temples, various types of Nilavilakku like 'Kutthuvilakku', 'Thookkuvilakku' etc are used and are very much related to the traditional beliefs and activities in Kerala.\n</p><p>Lighting the Nilavilakku on any occasion is believed to be auspicious. Nilavilakku plays an important role in the presentation of various art forms. The art forms are performed after lighting the lamp. In Kerala, many functions are inaugurated by lighting Nilavilakku.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>With the reach of Christianity in Kerala, <a href=\"/wiki/Saint_Thomas_Christians\" title=\"Saint Thomas Christians\">Saint Thomas Christians</a> (or Syrian Christians) also started keeping Nilavilakku in their churches and homes. Traditionally, the nilavilakku is lighted and kept at the main front entrance of a home. Syrian Christian art forms like <a href=\"/wiki/Margamkali\" title=\"Margamkali\">Margamkali</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Parichamuttukali\" title=\"Parichamuttukali\">Parichamuttukali</a> are performed around nilavilakku. A special type of Nilavilakku, called <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Aal_Vilakku&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Aal Vilakku (page does not exist)\">Aal Vilakku</a> is used in <a href=\"/wiki/Temple\" title=\"Temple\">Temples</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/South_India\" title=\"South India\">South India</a>, especially in <a href=\"/wiki/Kerala\" title=\"Kerala\">Kerala</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>It can find in some of the Muslim mosques like Ponnani Al Maqtoom Juma Masjid and Jarams (holy caves) in Kerala,\n</p><p>Nilavilakku is usually made of bronze or brass. Usually cotton wicks doused in oil or ghee are used for lighting the lamp. There are three ways of lighting the lamp. In one, only one wick is lit and is directed towards the deity or sacred space and in another there are two lit wicks in two directions. The third alternative is with five wicks in five directions.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Nilavilakku&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-Dance-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-ba